## 1. Context

Model the habitat suitability of *Tubastraea* spp. on the Brazilian coast, evaluating the potential risks of invasion in marine protected areas to support control and monitoring activities.

For more information, visit <https://github.com/ufsclabar/sun_coral_modeling/>.

## 4. Data configuration


### 4.1. Filter by proximity

Spatial autocorrelation, that is, when the values of variables sampled in nearby locations are not independent of each other (TOBLER, 1970), can lead to overfitting of the model to environmental conditions associated with characteristic geographic spaces, and generate inflated models (ARAÚJO; GUISAN, 2006; HIJMANS, 2012). In other words, samples within the range of spatial autocorrelation around a data point add little independent information but unduly inflate the sample size and thus the degrees of freedom of the model residuals, thereby biasing statistical inference. et al., 2007), occasionally even inverting the slope of the non-spatial analysis relationships (KÜHN, 2007). We resolve this disturbance through `filterByProximity`, which filters occurrence and absence records by their proximity to each other, respectively. In this way, we filter and exclude one point in every two, close by up to 10 km.

```{r, include=TRUE, eval=FALSE}
filterByProximity <- function(xy, dist, mapUnits = F) {
  if (!mapUnits) {
    d <- spDists(xy,longlat=T)
  }
  if (mapUnits) {
    d <- spDists(xy,longlat=F)
  }
  diag(d) <- NA
  close <- (d <= dist)
  diag(close) <- NA
  closePts <- which(close,arr.ind=T)
  discard <- matrix(nrow=2,ncol=2)
  if (nrow(closePts) > 0) {
    while (nrow(closePts) > 0) {
      if ((!paste(closePts[1,1],closePts[1,2],sep='_') %in% paste(discard[,1],discard[,2],sep='_')) & (!paste(closePts[1,2],closePts[1,1],sep='_') %in% paste(discard[,1],discard[,2],sep='_'))) {
        discard <- rbind(discard, closePts[1,])
        closePts <- closePts[-union(which(closePts[,1] == closePts[1,1]), which(closePts[,2] == closePts[1,1])),]
      }
    }
    discard <- discard[complete.cases(discard),]
    return(xy[-discard[,1],])
  }
  if (nrow(closePts) == 0) {
    return(xy)
  }
}
```

## 5. Reduction in data matrix

Excessively parameterized models, due to the inclusion of many environmental variables, for example, can cause model overfitting. And thus, selecting the main predictors in which to explore species habitat suitability, or at least being fully aware of overfitting, is a step of great importance in model design (PETERSON et al., 2011), and there are different biological or statistical criteria used to select the best set of variables.

Therefore, to reduce the data matrix in order to avoid overfitting the model, first, the correlations between all variables were examined using the `pairs.panels` and `corPlot` functions.


### 5.1. Examining correlations between all variables
```{r, include=TRUE, eval=FALSE}
myData <- sdmdata
describe(myData[,c(2:21)])

pairs.panels(myData[,c(2:21)],pch='.')
lowerCor(myData[,c(2:21)])
dev.off()
corPlot(myData[,c(2:21)], numbers=TRUE, main="Matriz de Correlação", n.legend=10, scale=FALSE)
```


### 5.2. Examining correlations between environmental variables: factor and principal components analyzes

We applied the parallel factors technique, through the `fa.parallel` function, and the Very Simple Structure adequacy test (VSS, REVELLE; ROCKLIN, 1979), through the `vss` function, to determine the ideal number of domains to be extracted from environmental variables.

```{r, include=TRUE, eval=FALSE}
fa.parallel(myData[,c(9:21)], fa='fa')
vss(myData[,c(9:21)])
```

4 factors were defined for the environmental variables.

#### 5.2.1. Factor analysis between environmental variables
```{r, include=TRUE, eval=FALSE}
fa.amb <- fa(myData[,c(9:21)], nfactors= 4, rotate= 'varimax')
plot(fa.amb)
fa.diagram(fa.amb)
```

#### 5.2.2. Principal component analysis between environmental variables
```{r, include=TRUE, eval=FALSE}
pca.amb <-principal(myData[,c(9:21)], 4, rotate="Promax")
plot(pca.amb)
fa.diagram(pca.amb)
```


### 5.3. Examining correlations between anthropogenic variables: factor and principal components analyzes

Likewise, the parallel factors technique was applied, through the `fa.parallel` function, and the Very Simple Structure adequacy test (VSS, REVELLE; ROCKLIN, 1979), through the `vss` function, to determine the number ideal domains to be extracted from the anthropic variables.

```{r, include=TRUE, eval=FALSE}
fa.parallel(myData[,c(2:8)], fa='fa')
vss(myData[,c(2:8)])
```

Two factors were chosen for the anthropogenic variables.

#### 5.3.1. Factor analysis between anthropogenic variables
```{r, include=TRUE, eval=FALSE}
fa.ant <- fa(myData[,c(2:8)], nfactors= 2, rotate= 'varimax')
plot(fa.ant)
fa.diagram(fa.ant)
```

#### 5.3.2. Principal component analysis between anthropogenic variables
```{r, include=TRUE, eval=FALSE}
pca.ant <-principal(myData[,c(2:8)], 2, rotate="Promax")
plot(pca.ant)
fa.diagram(pca.ant)
```



## 6. Habitat suitability modeling

Taking into account the classification of the variables in the domains after the FA and PCA analyses, 238 habitat suitability models for the sun coral were adjusted based on combinations between the predictors in three scenarios: (i) environmental variables, (ii) variables anthropogenic variables and (iii) environmental and anthropogenic variables. For each model, the distribution was analyzed using three DEM methodologies: *Generalized Linear Models* (GLM, MCCULLAGH et al., 1989) *Generalized Boosted Models* (GBM, RIDGEWAY, 2007) and *Random Forests* (RF, CUTLER et al., 2007). 75% of the occurrence and absence data were selected for training and the remaining 25% for testing, and each model was run twelve times for each method.

The *performance* of the models was evaluated using the *Receiver Operating Characteristic Curve* (ROC curve), sensitivity and specificity values. The ROC curve is a fundamental tool for evaluating diagnostic tests that demonstrates the diagnostic capacity of binary classifiers. (GRZYBOWSKI; YOUNGER, 1997). Finally, the sun coral invasion risk map was generated from a grouping of the models that presented the best performances, for this purpose a ROC of 0.7 was used as the *threshold* value. The importance of each variable in the models was evaluated using the `get_variables_importance` function and, finally, model projections were made.

## 7. Risk analysis

```{r, include=TRUE, eval=FALSE}
EMwmeanByROC_reclass <- raster("./Data/EMwmeanByROC_reclass.tif")
```


### 7.1. In ecoregions

To obtain the risk value in marine ecoregions and protected areas, we proposed the calculations specified below. For the Brazilian marine ecoregions, we summed the sun coral suitability values for each pixel in each of the eight ecoregions within the EEZ extent (sensu Spalding et al. 2007), and multiplied by the area of each ecoregion in in relation to the total area:

$$ R = \sum M \: . \: \left (\frac{a_{e}}{A} \right ) $$

where *M* is the suitability value of Tubastraea spp. for each pixel, *ae* is the area of each ecoregion, and *A* is the total area of the Brazilian Exclusive Economic Zone.

#### 7.1.1. Extracting the raster values for each ecoregion
```{r, include=TRUE, eval=FALSE}
amazonia <- extract(EMwmeanByROC_reclass, ecos_brasil[1,], df=TRUE)
amazonia$ID <- NULL
eastern_brazil <- extract(EMwmeanByROC_reclass, ecos_brasil[2,], df=TRUE)
eastern_brazil$ID <- NULL
fn_rocas <- extract(EMwmeanByROC_reclass, ecos_brasil[3,], df=TRUE)
fn_rocas$ID <- NULL
northeastern_brazil <- extract(EMwmeanByROC_reclass, ecos_brasil[4,], df=TRUE)
northeastern_brazil$ID <- NULL
rio_grande <- extract(EMwmeanByROC_reclass, ecos_brasil[5,], df=TRUE)
rio_grande$ID <- NULL
spsp_islands <- extract(EMwmeanByROC_reclass, ecos_brasil[6,], df=TRUE)
spsp_islands$ID <- NULL
southeastern_brazil <- extract(EMwmeanByROC_reclass, ecos_brasil[7,], df=TRUE)
southeastern_brazil$ID <- NULL
tmv_islands <- extract(EMwmeanByROC_reclass, ecos_brasil[8,], df=TRUE)
tmv_islands$ID <- NULL
```

#### 7.1.2. Adding the raster values for each ecoregion
```{r, include=TRUE, eval=FALSE}
soma_amazonia <- sum(amazonia$EMwmeanByROC, na.rm=TRUE)
soma_eastern_brazil <- sum(eastern_brazil$EMwmeanByROC, na.rm=TRUE)
soma_fn_rocas <- sum(fn_rocas$EMwmeanByROC, na.rm=TRUE)
soma_northeastern_brazil <- sum(northeastern_brazil$EMwmeanByROC, na.rm=TRUE)
soma_rio_grande <- sum(rio_grande$EMwmeanByROC, na.rm=TRUE)
soma_spsp_islands <- sum(spsp_islands$EMwmeanByROC, na.rm=TRUE)
soma_southeastern_brazil <- sum(southeastern_brazil$EMwmeanByROC, na.rm=TRUE)
soma_tmv_islands <- sum(tmv_islands$EMwmeanByROC, na.rm=TRUE)
```

#### 7.1.3. Calculating the total area of ecoregions
```{r, include=TRUE, eval=FALSE}
ecosAREAtotal <- sum(ecos_brasil$AREA)
ecosAREAtotal
```

#### 7.1.4. Calculating the risk value for each ecoregion
```{r, include=TRUE, eval=FALSE}
risco_amazonia <- soma_amazonia*(ecos_brasil$AREA[1]/ecosAREAtotal)
risco_eastern_brazil <- soma_eastern_brazil*(ecos_brasil$AREA[2]/ecosAREAtotal)
risco_fn_rocas <- soma_fn_rocas*(ecos_brasil$AREA[3]/ecosAREAtotal)
risco_northeastern_brazil <- soma_northeastern_brazil*(ecos_brasil$AREA[4]/ecosAREAtotal)
risco_rio_grande <- soma_rio_grande*(ecos_brasil$AREA[5]/ecosAREAtotal)
risco_spsp_islands <- soma_spsp_islands*(ecos_brasil$AREA[6]/ecosAREAtotal)
risco_southeastern_brazil <- soma_southeastern_brazil*(ecos_brasil$AREA[7]/ecosAREAtotal)
risco_tmv_islands <- soma_tmv_islands*(ecos_brasil$AREA[8]/ecosAREAtotal)
```


### 7.2. In marine protected areas

In the same way, to obtain the risk of invasion value in each marine protected area (ICMBio 2020), a calculation was made for a buffer of 111.11 km of each MPA, based on the suitability values of the sun coral for each pixel:

$$ R = \left ( \sum M \: . \: \left (\frac{a_{uc}}{A} \right ) \right )\: .\: N $$

where *M* is the suitability value of Tubastraea spp. for each pixel, *auc* is the area of each marine protected area, *A* is the total area of MPAs and *N* is the protection level of the MPA.
